The voyages and settlements of Aeneas before his arrival at Carthage. ’ “

THE time embraced in the narrative of this book is nearly seven years. It begins with the events immediately succeeding the sall of Troy, which oc- curred traditionally in 1184 nc. The Trojan fugitives, under the command of Aeneas, spent the remainder of the summer, and the following winter, in building ships in the ha'rbor of Antandros (sub Antandro), a city on the southern side of Mount Ida. This was the first year, i.e. the first summer and winter, after the fall of Troy. The second year begins with the depar- tureos the exiles (early in the summer) sor Thrace, and is spent in the attempt to establish a colony there (ll. 13-69). In the third year the new colony, called Aenos, or, as some think, Aenea, is abandoned, and the wan- derers, stopping at Delos to consult the oracle (l. 73), proceed to Crete (l. 131), and commence the colony of Pergameum (ll. 132-134). Having passed the fourth year and part of the fifth in Crete, they are compelled by a pestilence to give up this settlement also (l. 190), and sail to Actium in Acarnania, where they remain during the fifth winter (l. 284).
